**Two real bugs.** (1) `sort.Sort` mutates the caller's slice in place, so `topTwo` has the surprising side effect of reordering the argument — callers that still need the original order are silently broken. (2) `xs[:2]` panics if `len(xs) < 2`, and the returned slice still aliases the caller's backing array, so later writes to either affect both.

Work on a copy and guard the length:

```go
func topTwo(xs []int) []int {
	cp := append([]int(nil), xs...)
	sort.Sort(sort.Reverse(sort.IntSlice(cp)))
	n := 2
	if len(cp) < n {
		n = len(cp)
	}
	return cp[:n]
}
```

